Prologue
"Please!" begged Queen Eirwen. "Don't send her away! She's just a child!" King of Ice looked down at his wife from his throne, his royal advisor beside him. She had given birth to a daughter. He grimaced at the thought.
The little girl looked very much like her mother: pale blue eyes, white hair streaked with blue strands. King of Ice thought that a daughter would make him look weak. After all, he had only had sons until now.
"Your only options are to kill your child or send her back into the wild. This is her punishment for your bad behavior, Eirwen." He spat out her name as if it were poison. He always did.
Frostwell had not always been a single kingdom. It had been split into two, the North and the South. In the North, the non-magical kingdom. In the South, a kingdom filled with fantastical representations of power. Because of the North's greed, the two kingdoms had torn each other apart in an endless war, until the South proposed a truce.
The South was cornered, and its royal family would have done anything to stop the bloodshed. They proposed that their only princess become the queen of the North and bear a son destined to be the future king. Then, the South would have allied with the North to form a single kingdom. The North had accepted, and Princess Eirwen had married Prince Akull.
"I beg you, my highness, in exchange for my child's life, do whatever you want with me, imprison me, banish me, or even kill me," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child tightly in her arms.
King of Ice looked down at his wife, disgust in his eyes. Perhaps, perhaps he would have pity on her. The one with whom he had lived for twenty-two years, who had always taken care of him in his darkest hours, who had given birth to his sons.
"Very well, the child can live in the palace," he began, drawing a sigh of relief from his wife. "However," he added, "you will be executed."
The advisor and Queen Eirwen herself exchanged a horrified look. She gently lowered her gaze. "Yes, highness," she said, bowing.
The King of Ice ordered the royal advisor to take the child to one of Eirwen's vacant apartments. Once this was done, he ordered the guards to take Eirwen to the execution site, where all the townspeople could witness the spectacle.
As the guards escorted her to the site, the townspeople cried out in indignation at seeing their only queen, the kindest one, about to be killed. Some people were crying, others were shouting and trying to attack the guards, while others were wondering what was happening, but all were outraged.
"Free her!"
"Why are they doing this to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden gallows, the most feared person in the kingdom entered. The fire wielder. Ex-Queen Eirwen was going to be burned alive. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the cruelest punishment in Frostfell.
Eirwen was tied to the stake, and the king began to explain how the queen had betrayed them all. The people of Frostfell refused to believe him and never accepted his words. Then, the fire wielder set the stake alight, and a single tear rolled down the ex-queen's cheek.
"Survive, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Silence in the corridors
Tap, tap, tap. These were the only sounds emanating from the farthest room on the left of the always-frozen south wing of the palace. The attendants passing by always wondered what was in this room, frightened of what might be inside. The rumors of the maids danced through the corridors. It was thought that the late wife of the King of Ice, Eirwen, was in this room, waiting to be freed.
"They couldn't be more wrong," thought Ivory as he walked toward the south wing, while the attendants went back and forth murmuring among themselves. They don't at all know what is in this room.
Of course, these rumors also applied to iel, because iel was the only person allowed to enter the room.
Tap Tap. "Miss Kari, are you there?" murmured Ivory to the finely decorated door, covered in snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Iel wondered if she would invite him in, unlike other times when iel had asked her. I still have bruises from the previous time. Ivory chuckled at that memory. Kari had thrown a book at his shoulder, but when she realized who it was, she immediately apologized.
A single knock comes from inside, which seemed to mean that she was there, but after all, where else could she be?
"Can I come in?" asked Ivory, remembering the time when iel had done so without asking for permission.
A knock came from inside. It seemed to mean yes. Ivory shivered, from the cold, but also because of the sound. It was strange for Ivory to hear noise coming from a supposedly empty room, even though iel had entered this room for years.
"Here I am," said Ivory, gently opening the door. The scene inside the room was unusual by normal standards, but not unexpected. There were papers everywhere. Books were scattered, the desk was broken, and a multitude of ice statues were scattered around. The room had no windows and almost no light. It was also colder than the rest of the palace (and that was saying something). A snowstorm seemed to have descended inside.
The girl there was curled up in bed, wrapped in her blanket, where she was reading one of her notebooks. A small lantern lit the space.
"Which notebook is this?" asked Ivory, sitting next to Kari on her bed.
